# Part 8 — Recommended Habits

Do:

* Use one `.venv` per project
* Commit often
* Write clear commit messages
* Use branches for larger changes
* Commit `.python-version`
* Commit `pyproject.toml`
* Commit `uv.lock`
* Keep notebooks clean before committing
* Keep raw or private data out of Git

Avoid:

* Installing packages globally
* Committing `.venv`
* Committing passwords or API keys
* Committing large raw datasets
* Mixing pip, conda, Poetry, PDM, and uv in the same project
* Working directly on `main` for large changes

---

# Quick Reference

Create a new project:

```powershell
mkdir my-project
cd my-project
git init
pyenv local 3.13.7
uv init
uv venv
.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
uv add pandas numpy matplotlib (if you need to install new libraries)
code .
```

Daily commands:

```powershell
git status
git add .
git commit -m "Describe the change"
git push
```

Run code:

```powershell
uv run python src/main.py
```

Sync existing project:

```powershell
git clone <repository-url>
cd project-name
pyenv install
uv sync
code .
```
